@jgeewax How do you mean the way we currently document it? We don't document it anywhere.

Current the module is public, but this change makes it private, which means we don't guarantee the interface to users.

@tseaver Whether we make it public or not, people can always re-generate this file by using the `protoc` compiler with the [spec][1]. By making the module private, we are just saying we don't guarantee the interface (which we don't).

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-datastore/blob/21e029b2657ebb15fef5429c90c4315326855fd1/proto/datastore_v1.proto

I think I'm going to flip-flop my opinion on this.

The purpose of `TransactionContext` is to provide the transaction level data necessary for vm execution, i.e. the `gas_price` and the `origin` address.

@dylanjw I think a common base for the transaction classes which implements the intrinsic gas calculations should be fine.  I don't think there is anything in the signed vs unsigned that restricts either from being able to compute the intrinsic gas costs.

I would be okay, but I would keep it for another PR (maybe `v0.3`).

At the cost of doing this, I'd like to have an object like `PluginTester` so that we do something like :

    class TestTerminator(PluginTester):
        def test_main(self):
            ...

but `PluginTester` would also have a method we could use to generate all the test examples for the doc. I think it's too bad to implement nice maps in the test and have to re-implement it in notebooks for docs and examples.

